summary:
1. Decides all States shall refrain from supporting non-State actors attempting to develop, acquire, manufacture, possess, transport, transfer, or use nuclear, chemical, or biological weapons and their means of delivery;
2. Decides all States shall adopt and enforce laws prohibiting non-State actors from manufacturing, acquiring, possessing, developing, transporting, transferring, or using such weapons and their means of delivery.
The Security Council:
1. Decides that all States shall take and enforce effective measures to prevent the proliferation of nuclear, chemical, or biological weapons and their means of delivery, including attempts to engage in, participate in, assist or finance such activities;
2. Requires all States to prohibit activities related to nuclear, chemical, or biological weapons, including attempts to engage in any such activities, participate in them as an accomplice, assist or finance them;
3. Mandates all States to:
    (a) Account for and secure such items in production, use, storage or transport;
    (b) Develop and maintain physical protection measures;
    (c) Establish border controls and law enforcement efforts to detect, deter, prevent and combat illicit trafficking;
    (d) Establish national export and trans-shipment controls over such items, including laws and regulations to control export, transit, trans-shipment and re-export;
4. Establishes a Committee of the Security Council for a period of no longer than two years, to report on the implementation of this resolution, and requests States to present a first report no later than six months;
5. Clarifies that the obligations set forth in this resolution do not conflict with or alter the rights and obligations of State Parties to relevant treaties;
6. Recognizes the utility of effective national control lists and calls upon all Member States to pursue their development;
7. Invites States to offer assistance to States lacking the infrastructure, experience, and resources to implement the provisions;
8. Calls upon all States:
    (a) To promote the universal adoption and full implementation of multilateral treaties;
    (b) To adopt national rules and regulations to ensure compliance with their commitments;
    (c) To renew and fulfil their commitment to multilateral cooperation;
    (d) To develop ways to work with industry and the public regarding their obligations;
9. Calls upon all States to promote dialogue and cooperation on non-proliferation;
